      "When you stop smoking, your body and brain have to get used to not having nicotine, which can be uncomfortable. Nicotine withdrawal can't hurt you, though, unless you give in and have a cigarette. Over time, withdrawal symptoms fade as long as you stay smokefree.",
      "Cravings or urges to smoke are one of the most common withdrawal symptoms. Almost everyone who smokes regularly has cravings when they quit; they may be mild or can sometimes feel overwhelming. Quit-smoking medicines, physical activity, avoiding your triggers, and remembering your reasons for quitting can all help you get through an urge.",
