      "Nicotine is addictive because it drives compulsive use despite negative health consequences, which is the hallmark of addiction. This is why quitting is so hard: roughly half of smokers try to quit each year, but only about 6 percent succeed in any given year, and most people need several attempts before they stop for good. Repeated quit attempts are normal and expected, not a sign of failure.",
      "When someone uses nicotine, it produces a brief feeling of pleasure or euphoria, partly through a surge of endorphins in the brain's reward circuits. More importantly, nicotine increases levels of the neurotransmitter dopamine in those same reward circuits. This dopamine signal reinforces the behavior, teaching the brain to seek out nicotine again and again.",
      "A major reason nicotine is so addictive is how fast it acts. When inhaled, nicotine reaches the brain within about 10 seconds, but the effect fades quickly. This rapid rise and fall pushes people to use again soon to keep the effect going and to avoid the discomfort that follows, creating a tight cycle of repeated dosing throughout the day.",
      "Over time, ongoing nicotine exposure changes how the brain works. It alters the brain's sensitivity and affects circuits involved in learning, stress, and self-control. These lasting changes help explain why cravings and the pull to use can persist well beyond the first days of quitting.",
