      "Vaping devices, also called electronic cigarettes or e-cigarettes, are battery-operated tools that let users inhale an aerosol typically containing nicotine, flavorings, and other chemicals. Their designs range from shapes that resemble traditional cigarettes to forms disguised as everyday items like pens or USB sticks. Most contain four parts: a cartridge or pod holding e-liquid with varying amounts of nicotine, a heating element (atomizer), a battery, and a mouthpiece. When the user puffs, the battery activates the heater, which vaporizes the liquid for inhalation.",
      "When a person vapes, nicotine is rapidly absorbed from the lungs into the bloodstream. It stimulates the adrenal glands to release epinephrine (adrenaline), which raises blood pressure, breathing rate, and heart rate. Like other addictive substances, nicotine activates the brain's reward circuits and increases dopamine, which reinforces repeated use despite the health risks.",
      "Nicotine in any form is a highly addictive drug, and vaping can lead to nicotine addiction. Research indicates nicotine can prime the brain's reward system, putting vapers at increased risk for addiction to other drugs as well. This combination of strong physical absorption and reward-circuit reinforcement is what makes the habit so difficult to break.",
      "Vaping devices are the most commonly used form of nicotine among youth in the United States, and they are especially popular among teens. Many teens do not realize the cartridges contain nicotine at all. Easy availability, appealing advertisements, a wide variety of flavors, and a perception that vaping is safer than cigarettes all drive youth adoption. The devices are also easy to conceal and do not produce the odor of tobacco smoke.",
      "The teen years are a critical period for brain development that continues into young adulthood, which makes young nicotine users especially vulnerable to long-lasting effects. Because nicotine affects developing reward systems, continued vaping can cause nicotine addiction and make other drugs such as cocaine and methamphetamine more pleasurable to the developing brain. Nicotine also affects brain circuits that control attention and learning, and additional risks include mood disorders and permanent problems with impulse control.",
      "Early evidence suggests vaping may act as an introductory product that leads to cigarette use. Ninth-graders who used e-cigarettes were more likely to later smoke traditional cigarettes, and one study found high school students who had recently used e-cigarettes were about seven times more likely to report smoking cigarettes roughly six months later. A study also found that about one in four high school students used e-cigarettes for 'dripping,' placing e-liquid directly on heated coils, citing thicker vapor, enhanced flavor, and a stronger throat sensation.",
