      "Smoking causes at least 11 types of cancer, including lung, throat, mouth, esophageal, stomach, pancreatic, kidney, bladder, and cervical cancers, as well as acute myeloid leukemia. A smoker's risk of cancer is 2 to 10 times higher than that of a person who has never smoked, depending on how long and how much they have smoked. Smoking is also linked to heart disease, stroke, emphysema, bronchitis, cataracts, and bone disease.",
      "Quitting smoking lowers cancer risk over time. People who quit reduce their lung cancer risk by 30% to 50% after 10 years compared with people who keep smoking. The risk of mouth and esophageal cancer drops by about half within 5 years after quitting.",
      "Nicotine is the addictive substance in tobacco, and breaking that addiction is central to quitting. When a person stops using nicotine, they may experience withdrawal symptoms such as feeling depressed or nervous, having trouble thinking clearly, or having trouble sleeping. Cessation medications work in part by reducing these withdrawal symptoms.",
      "Healthcare providers play a key role in helping people quit by asking about smoking at every visit, advising the person to quit, assessing their willingness to do so, and helping them plan. A typical plan includes setting a quit date, providing self-help materials, recommending drug treatment, and scheduling follow-up appointments. This structured provider involvement improves the chances of successfully quitting.",
      "Behavioral counseling improves quit rates, especially when combined with other support. In the Lung Health Study, heavy smokers who received doctor counseling along with group behavioral sessions involving other smokers had better quit rates and a reduced risk of lung cancer, other cancers, heart disease, and respiratory disease. Combining counseling with medication tends to work better than either approach alone.",
      "Peer counseling can be particularly effective for certain groups. Childhood cancer survivors responded better to peer-counseling programs, in which trained survivors support others trying to quit, than to self-help approaches alone. Matching the type of support to the person's situation can improve outcomes.",
      "Nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) supplies controlled amounts of nicotine to ease withdrawal and help break the addiction. NRT products include nicotine gum, patches, nasal spray, inhalers, and lozenges, and they can be used alone or in combination. They help reduce withdrawal symptoms such as depression, nervousness, difficulty concentrating, and sleep problems.",
      "Two non-nicotine prescription medications are used to help people quit smoking: bupropion (sold as Zyban) and varenicline (sold as Chantix). Both reduce nicotine cravings and withdrawal symptoms. They are taken under a healthcare provider's guidance as part of a quit plan.",
      "Cessation medications carry safety considerations that should be discussed with a healthcare provider. Bupropion and varenicline may cause serious psychiatric effects, including changes in behavior, aggression, anxiety, depression, and suicidal thoughts. Varenicline may also cause serious heart problems.",
      "Nicotine replacement therapy is not appropriate for everyone. It is generally not recommended for people who are pregnant or breastfeeding, for teenagers, or for those with heart rhythm problems, uncontrolled high blood pressure, esophagitis, ulcers, insulin-dependent diabetes, or asthma. People in these groups should talk with a healthcare provider before using NRT.",
      "Cutting back on cigarettes is less effective than quitting completely and can carry hidden risks. People who reduce how much they smoke may inhale more deeply or smoke more of each cigarette, which offsets some of the benefit. Nicotine replacement products can help reduce the number of cigarettes smoked, but this effect does not appear to last over time, so full cessation remains the goal.",
      "Free resources are available to support quitting. These include the website www.smokefree.gov, the QuitGuide app, and the booklet Clearing the Air: Quit Smoking Today, which can be requested by calling 1-800-422-6237."
