      "Despite progress in reducing smoking prevalence in the United States, smoking remains a major threat to public health. Reductions in smoking have been uneven across the population, and prevalence continues to remain high among certain sub-populations. Research in this area covers the causes of tobacco use as well as a broad range of behavioral and pharmacological interventions to help people stop smoking.",
      "Free, evidence-based smoking cessation support is available through publicly funded online and mobile resources. These include cessation websites, SMS text-messaging quit programs, smartphone apps, and social media support, offered in both English and Spanish. The goal is to provide on-demand information and support to people trying to quit.",
      "Cessation support programs can be tailored to specific groups who may face distinct challenges when quitting. Specialized programs exist for women, teens, veterans, and adults over 60. Matching support to a person's circumstances is part of an evidence-based approach to cessation.",
      "Integrating tobacco cessation treatment into routine cancer care helps patients who smoke quit. Initiatives have worked to help cancer centers build and sustain tobacco cessation treatment programs and to address cessation routinely with cancer patients. This is done in part by refining electronic medical records and clinical workflows so that cessation treatment is offered consistently.",
      "Smoking cessation can be effectively delivered in the context of lung cancer screening. Research collaborations develop and test approaches that connect people undergoing lung cancer screening with cessation treatment. Pairing screening visits with cessation support reaches smokers at a moment when they are engaged with the health system.",
      "Tobacco use frequently co-occurs with other substance use. Research that integrates resources across alcohol, drug abuse, and cancer programs addresses poly-substance or multi-substance use, abuse, and addiction together. Recognizing these overlapping addictions can inform more comprehensive cessation and treatment strategies."
