    "chunks": [
      "Nicotine addiction is driven by how nicotine interacts with receptors and neurotransmitter systems in the brain to create dependence, craving, and withdrawal. Understanding this neurobiology explains why quitting smoking is physically difficult and not simply a matter of willpower.",
      "Most of the nicotine a person takes in (roughly 70 to 80 percent) is broken down into cotinine in the liver by microsomal enzymes. The enzyme cytochrome P450 2A6 (CYP2A6) is responsible for about 90 percent of this breakdown and is the main pathway that deactivates nicotine in humans.",
      "Inherited differences in the CYP2A6 gene appear to influence smoking behavior. People who metabolize nicotine more slowly because of variations in this gene may be partly protected from becoming nicotine-dependent smokers, since slower metabolism changes how nicotine accumulates and is cleared.",
      "Nicotine raises the level of dopamine outside cells in the nucleus accumbens, a key reward region of the brain. It does this by activating the mesolimbic dopamine system through nicotinic receptors located in the ventral tegmental area (VTA) and the nucleus accumbens, which is central to the rewarding, reinforcing feeling of smoking.",
      "Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors come in different subunit combinations, and nicotine is most sensitive at the alpha-4 beta-2 receptor arrangement. Experiments in mice bred to lack the beta-2 subunit (knockout mice) showed reduced addictive responses, identifying that subunit as important to nicotine's addictive properties.",
      "Repeated tobacco use delivers pulses of nicotine to the central nervous system while keeping a steady background level of nicotine in the blood throughout the day of smoking. This continuous exposure leads the nicotinic receptors to become desensitized, which shapes the cycle of tolerance and craving that smokers experience.",
      "The first cigarette of the day tends to feel the most rewarding because the overnight break from smoking lets desensitized nicotinic receptors recover and become active again. As the number of active receptor sites increases overnight and into the early morning, withdrawal symptoms and craving intensify, which is why the morning urge to smoke is often strongest.",
      "Brain imaging with PET scans shows that tobacco use produces a marked reduction in the activity of monoamine oxidase (MAO), the enzyme that normally breaks down dopamine. Lowering both forms of this enzyme, MAO-A and MAO-B, results in higher dopamine levels, adding to nicotine's reinforcing effect beyond its direct action on nicotinic receptors.",
      "Nicotine also acts on other neurotransmitter systems involved in mood and reward. Nicotinic agonists trigger a calcium-dependent release of GABA in parts of the brain, and ongoing daily nicotine exposure lowers serotonin (5-HT) activity in the hippocampus, changes that contribute to the mood disturbances felt during withdrawal.",
      "Nicotine is a toxic substance, and the estimated toxic dose is around 40 to 60 mg in adults, roughly 0.8 to 1 mg per kilogram of body weight, with a much lower threshold of about 10 mg in children. This underscores that nicotine-containing products should be kept away from children and used cautiously."
    ]
