    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Two things make quitting smoking difficult: your brain has to get used to not having nicotine around, and you have to get used to daily routines that no longer include smoking. To quit successfully, you have to deal with both of these challenges at once, which is part of why quitting is hard.",
      "Nicotine is the main addictive drug in tobacco and is what makes quitting so hard. Cigarettes are designed to rapidly deliver nicotine to your brain. Inside the brain, nicotine triggers the release of chemicals that make you feel good, and as nicotine stimulates parts of your brain over and over, your brain gets used to having nicotine around.",
      "Over time, nicotine changes how your brain works and makes it seem like you need nicotine just to feel okay. This brain adaptation is the core of nicotine addiction and explains why stopping feels so uncomfortable at first.",
      "When you stop smoking, your brain gets irritable, and you might feel anxious or upset, have a hard time concentrating or sleeping, have strong urges to smoke, or just feel generally uncomfortable. These feelings are called withdrawal. Withdrawal gets better a few weeks after quitting, as your brain gets used to not having nicotine around.",
      "Some quit-smoking medicines contain nicotine. This gives you a safe way to get used to not having so much nicotine from cigarettes in your brain. Nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) works this way and can help you quit smoking for good.",
      "Your days are filled with routines that you associate with smoking, and when you quit it may be hard to do these routines without a cigarette in your hand. Many people connect smoking with things they do during the day, like taking breaks, drinking a cup of coffee, finishing a meal, talking with friends, or using the phone. These cues are called triggers.",
      "Feelings can also trigger an urge to smoke. People can get urges when they start to feel stressed or down, or even when feeling happy or relaxed, so after quitting, any of these feelings can trigger the urge to smoke. When you quit, you will figure out how to get through your routines without cigarettes and how to deal with feeling stressed or down without smoking.",
      "Quit-smoking medicines help with the brain side of quitting by reducing cravings and withdrawal symptoms like being irritable and having trouble concentrating and sleeping. That allows you to focus on the second challenge: figuring out how to get through the day doing all the activities you connected to smoking. Quitline coaches can also help you come up with ways to make quitting easier.",
      "The good news is that millions of people have quit smoking for good, and most report feeling better after they have been quit for a while. Successful quitting means handling both your brain not having nicotine and not having cigarettes during your daily routines, and there are many simple things that make this easier."
    ]
