    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Many smokers worry about gaining weight when they quit, but it is better for your health to quit smoking as soon as possible. Weight gain after quitting can be managed with four main strategies: controlling appetite, exercising regularly, eating mindfully, and finding non-food ways to cope with emotions.",
      "Smoking cigarettes makes you feel less hungry, so when you quit smoking you might feel hungrier and eat more. Practicing portion control can help you prevent overeating after you quit. Staying hydrated also helps, because thirst can be mistaken for hunger.",
      "Smoking cigarettes increases your metabolism, so smokers burn more calories; when you stop smoking, you may burn fewer calories. Regular physical activity helps maintain calorie burn after quitting. Just 10 minutes of exercise a day can make a difference.",
      "Eating can become a substitute for smoking after you quit, but it doesn't have to. Mindful eating means preparing, choosing, and eating food with awareness. To eat mindfully, eliminate distractions such as your phone, TV, or computer during meals, and eat at the dinner table so you can focus on your food.",
      "To avoid overeating after quitting smoking, think carefully about your portion sizes and consider starting with a smaller portion; you can always take more if you are still hungry. Avoid serving food family-style, which encourages automatic second helpings. Before eating more, do a belly check to determine whether you are genuinely hungry or eating for emotional reasons.",
      "After quitting smoking, people often turn to food when they feel stressed or experience negative emotions. Instead of using eating as a substitute for cigarettes, learn other ways to cope with stress and difficult feelings without smoking. Strategies such as exercising to fight cravings, boosting your mood, and practicing mindfulness can replace both smoking and emotional eating."
    ]
