    "chunks": [
      "People with mental illness smoke at much higher rates than the general population. In 2019, past-month cigarette smoking was 1.8 times higher among people with any past-year mental illness than among those without (28.2% vs. 15.8%). Rates are highest with serious mental illness: an estimated 70-85% of people with schizophrenia and 50-70% of people with bipolar disorder smoke.",
      "People with mental illness who have ever smoked are also less likely to have quit. Among lifetime smokers, 66% of those with mental illness still smoked in the past month, compared with 47.4% of lifetime smokers without mental illness.",
      "Smoking is especially common among people with substance use disorders. Past-month smoking was 35.8% for adults with a past-year substance use disorder versus 16.8% for those without, and among people in addiction treatment, smoking rates range from roughly 65-85%.",
      "Adults with both tobacco addiction and mental illness (excluding substance use disorders) make up only 7.1% of the U.S. population, yet they consume 34.2% of all cigarettes smoked in the U.S. On average they smoke about 331 cigarettes per month, compared with 310 for smokers in the general population.",
      "One proposed reason people with mental illness smoke more is that nicotine may temporarily ease symptoms such as poor concentration, low mood, and stress. This short-term relief may contribute to the higher smoking prevalence seen among people with depression and schizophrenia, even though the relief does not treat the underlying condition.",
      "The health toll of smoking in this population is severe. Tobacco-related diseases account for approximately 53% of deaths among people with schizophrenia, 48% among people with bipolar disorder, and 50% among people with depression.",
      "Evidence-based quit-smoking treatments work for people with mental illness without making psychiatric symptoms worse. People with schizophrenia showed better quit rates with the medication bupropion compared with placebo, with no worsening of psychiatric symptoms. A combination of the medication varenicline and behavioral support has shown promise for helping people with bipolar disorder and major depressive disorder quit, also with no worsening of psychiatric symptoms.",
      "Combining medication with talk therapy improves long-term quitting for people with serious mental illness. Varenicline plus cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) was more effective than CBT alone at helping people with serious mental illness stop smoking for a prolonged period, both after 1 year of treatment and at 6 months after treatment ended.",
      "Quitting smoking is linked with improved mental health, not worse. Smoking cessation has been associated with reduced depression, anxiety, and stress, as well as enhanced mood and quality of life. In addition, smokers who are receiving mental health treatment achieve higher quit rates than those without such support.",
      "Having a mental disorder increases the risk of relapse back to smoking, particularly in response to stress and negative emotions. This elevated relapse risk persists even after sustained abstinence of more than one year, so ongoing coping strategies for stress and low mood remain important long after quitting."
    ]
