      "In a September 2025 blog post, NIDA Director Dr. Nora Volkow discusses the potential for developing FDA-approved e-cigarettes as therapeutic smoking cessation aids. She acknowledges a public health paradox around vaping: commercial devices are optimized for nicotine delivery and appeal to youth, and initiation with vape products in adolescence can be a steppingstone to taking up cigarette smoking, yet vaping does not present the worst health risks associated with combustible tobacco and can facilitate smoking cessation in adults.",
      "A 2024 Cochrane systematic review found that nicotine e-cigarettes can help people stop smoking for at least six months and that they outperform nicotine replacement therapy (NRT). Randomized controlled trials in which smokers received e-cigarettes free as a therapeutic intervention have shown quit-success effects supporting this conclusion.",
      "Major health bodies have begun recognizing e-cigarettes in adult smoking cessation: the American Society of Addiction Medicine recognizes switching to e-cigarettes as an approach to reducing the harms of combusted tobacco, and the UK National Health Service recommends e-cigarettes as quit aids for smokers.",
      "As of 2025, the FDA has authorized 39 e-cigarette devices for sale to adults as tobacco products, but no electronic cigarette has ever been approved as a smoking cessation therapeutic. As of the previous year, the FDA had received no applications seeking approval of such a product. E-cigarette technology emerged over two decades ago and devices have been commercially available since 2007, meaning long-term safety data are still limited.",
      "NIDA is funding trials that compare e-cigarettes and heated tobacco products against traditional nicotine replacement medications in smokers who previously failed to quit, as well as randomized clinical trials examining e-cigarettes as quit aids for people in treatment for opioid use disorder and other substance use disorders.",
      "NIDA-funded research is also examining how nicotine from e-cigarettes deposits in the brain compared with traditional cigarettes, and comparing health biomarkers in people using standard research e-cigarettes versus those with dual-use patterns (using both e-cigarettes and combustible cigarettes). The NIH is soliciting applications for tobacco regulatory science studies on the cardiovascular, pulmonary, neurodevelopmental, and neuropsychiatric effects of e-cigarettes, their addictive potential, and their behavioral impacts.",
      "Volkow proposes that reduced-smoking endpoints, not only complete abstinence, may warrant FDA acceptance in evaluating cessation products if reduction provides meaningful clinical benefits or increases the likelihood of eventual cessation. This would broaden how success is measured in smoking cessation trials.",
      "The core argument is that, given the catastrophic health burden of combustible tobacco, developing e-cigarettes as regulated FDA-approved therapeutics could provide assurance of safety and efficacy that commercial vaping products lack. Approval as a cessation therapeutic could also expand access through insurance reimbursement and through expedited FDA review pathways available for smoking cessation products."
