    "chunks": [
      "In 2015, 16.7 percent of adult males and 13.6 percent of adult females in the U.S. smoked cigarettes. The differences in how men and women respond to smoking and quitting are thought to involve a mix of physiological factors, particularly ovarian hormones, as well as cultural and behavioral factors. Understanding these differences can help tailor approaches to quitting.",
      "Research suggests that smoking activates the brain's reward pathways more strongly in men than in women. Men appear to be motivated more by nicotine's reinforcing effects, whereas women tend to smoke to manage their mood or in response to smoking-related cues in their environment. This difference means the same quitting strategy may not work equally well for everyone.",
      "Nicotine relieves withdrawal symptoms and negative mood more effectively in men than in women. In studies, smoking a cigarette containing nicotine, compared with a de-nicotinized cigarette, eased withdrawal symptoms and improved negative mood to a greater extent in men. For women, the nicotine itself provides less relief from these symptoms.",
      "Stress and the hormone cortisol play different roles in relapse for men and women. During withdrawal, men were more likely to relapse when their cortisol levels were low, while women were more likely to relapse when their cortisol levels were high. Women also experience stronger stress-induced cravings, whereas men respond more strongly to environmental smoking cues.",
      "Women tend to have a harder time quitting smoking successfully than men. Research found women were 31 percent less likely to quit successfully. Concerns about weight gain after quitting may also hinder women's success rates, making this a useful issue to address as part of a quit plan.",
      "The medication varenicline has shown greater effectiveness in women than men at the 3-to-6-month mark, although 1-year quit rates were equal between the sexes. By contrast, a combination of varenicline plus bupropion was less effective for cessation among women compared with men. This suggests medication choice may benefit from being matched to the individual."
    ]
