      "Evidence-based smoking cessation treatment includes behavioral counseling and FDA-approved cessation medications. The combination of behavioral counseling and medication is especially effective, increasing the chances of quitting successfully compared with using either approach alone. Quitting smoking dramatically reduces the risk of lung and other cancers caused by smoking, as well as the risk of coronary heart disease, stroke, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.",
      "In 2022-2023, 32.3% of U.S. adults aged 18 and older who attempted to quit smoking in the past year used some form of evidence-based cessation treatment (95% confidence interval: 30.7-33.9). Use differed by sex: 29.3% of male quit-attempters used treatment compared with 35.8% of females. From 2018-2019 to 2022-2023, the overall change in cessation treatment use was not statistically significant.",
      "FDA-approved cessation medications include various forms of nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) - the patch, gum, lozenge, nasal spray, and oral inhaler - plus two medications that do not contain nicotine: bupropion (also known as Zyban) and varenicline (also known as Chantix). In 2022-2023, 29.7% of adults who attempted to quit smoking in the past year used a cessation medication (95% confidence interval: 28.2-31.2), making medication far more commonly used than counseling.",
      "Behavioral counseling for quitting smoking can be delivered through telephone quitlines, clinician-led individual sessions, classes, support groups, web-based programs, smartphone apps, and text-messaging programs. In 2022-2023, only 8.6% of adults who attempted to quit smoking used counseling (95% confidence interval: 7.7-9.6). Women used counseling at notably higher rates than men: 11.5% of female quit-attempters versus 6.1% of males.",
      "The U.S. Surgeon General has concluded that there is presently inadequate evidence to conclude that e-cigarettes, in general, increase smoking cessation. No e-cigarette has been approved by the FDA as a therapeutic product for smoking cessation treatment. Similarly, the 2020 Surgeon General's Report on Smoking Cessation concluded that evidence is inadequate to infer that smartphone apps for smoking cessation are independently effective on their own in increasing smoking cessation.",
      "The Healthy People 2030 initiative sets a national target of increasing the proportion of adult smokers who use evidence-based cessation counseling and/or medication during quit attempts to 43.8%, compared with about 32.3% in 2022-2023. The Healthy People 2030 measure relies on National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) data, while the National Cancer Institute's progress tracking uses the Tobacco Use Supplement to the Current Population Survey.",
      "Usage gaps highlight an opportunity for people trying to quit smoking: while 29.7% of quit-attempters used medication in 2022-2023, only 8.6% used behavioral counseling, even though combining counseling with medication is especially effective. Free, evidence-based counseling options include telephone quitlines, support groups, classes, web-based programs, and text-message programs."
