      "Smoking causes about 30 percent of all cancer deaths in the United States each year. The American Cancer Society estimated that in 2022, roughly 182,808 of the 609,360 U.S. cancer deaths were attributable to cigarette smoking. This makes quitting smoking one of the most powerful single actions a person can take to reduce their cancer risk.",
      "Cigarette smoking is linked to cancers throughout the body, not just the lungs. It is associated with cancers of the lung, esophagus, larynx, mouth, throat, kidney, bladder, liver, pancreas, stomach, cervix, colon, and rectum, as well as acute myeloid leukemia. Quitting reduces exposure to the carcinogens driving these risks.",
      "There is no safe level of smoking. According to the National Cancer Institute's Cancer Trends Progress Report, individuals who smoke even a few cigarettes per month over their lifetime are at a higher risk of smoking-related death than those who have never smoked. Cutting down alone is not enough; complete cessation is what eliminates this excess risk.",
      "Quitting works at a population level: adult cigarette smoking prevalence in the United States has steadily declined from 42 percent in 1964, when the first Surgeon General's Report on the harms of smoking was published, to 11.0 percent in 2023, based on National Health Interview Survey data spanning 1965 to 2023. The national Healthy People 2030 goal is to reduce adult smoking prevalence further, to 6.1 percent. People who quit today join a decades-long majority shift away from smoking.",
      "As of 2023, 11.0 percent of U.S. adults aged 18 and older currently smoked cigarettes, 7.1 percent used e-cigarettes, 4.0 percent used cigars, and 2.2 percent used smokeless tobacco. Among adults who smoke cigarettes, 8.0 percent smoked daily and 3.0 percent smoked nondaily. Some people who quit cigarettes use more than one nicotine product, so a quit plan should account for all forms of tobacco and nicotine use.",
      "Smoking rates vary widely by demographic group, which shapes who benefits most from cessation support. In 2023, current cigarette smoking was 14.4 percent among American Indian/Alaska Native adults, 12.5 percent among non-Hispanic White adults, 12.0 percent among non-Hispanic Black adults, 8.1 percent among Hispanic adults, and 5.2 percent among non-Hispanic Asian adults. Men smoked at higher rates than women, 12.8 percent versus 9.3 percent.",
      "Socioeconomic factors are strongly tied to smoking. In 2023, among adults aged 25 and older, 21.8 percent of those with less than a high school education smoked, compared with 17.5 percent of high school graduates and 8.8 percent of those with education beyond high school. Adults living below 200 percent of the federal poverty level smoked at more than double the rate of higher-income adults, 18.2 percent versus 8.5 percent. These disparities mean cessation gains are not evenly distributed and targeted quit support matters.",
      "E-cigarette use among adults shows a different age pattern than cigarette smoking. In 2023, 13.2 percent of adults aged 18 to 24 used e-cigarettes compared with 6.2 percent of adults 25 and older, while cigarette smoking was only 3.4 percent in the 18-to-24 group versus 12.1 percent among those 25 and older. Among young adults, 14.5 percent of men and 12.0 percent of women used e-cigarettes, indicating vaping has largely replaced cigarettes as the dominant nicotine product in the youngest adult cohort."
