      "E-cigarettes are electronic nicotine delivery systems (ENDS) or electronic non-nicotine delivery systems (ENNDS). They heat a liquid to create an aerosol that contains nicotine and toxic substances such as formaldehyde, which harm both the user and people exposed secondhand.",
      "E-cigarette use increases the risk of cardiovascular diseases and lung disorders. Nicotine is highly addictive and damages adolescent brain development. Evidence suggests that minors who have never smoked but use e-cigarettes at least double their chance of starting to smoke conventional tobacco cigarettes later in life.",
      "E-cigarettes are often used alongside conventional cigarettes rather than replacing them: approximately 70% of adult e-cigarette users in the USA also smoke conventional cigarettes. This dual use maintains exposure to the harms of both products.",
      "Scientific evidence that e-cigarettes work as smoking cessation aids remains inconclusive. While some smokers switch to e-cigarettes, very few stop using them entirely, and switching is not quitting because it maintains exposure to nicotine and toxic compounds.",
      "The WHO recommends proven cessation methods for quitting nicotine: brief advice from healthcare workers, toll-free quit lines, digital cessation services such as text message programs, nicotine replacement therapy (gums and patches), bupropion, and varenicline.",
      "Quit lines also help people who use e-cigarettes, not just cigarette smokers. The largest quit line operator in the United States served 74,646 participants between January 2017 and June 2020, and 14% of those participants were e-cigarette users.",
      "Quit line services appear roughly as effective for e-cigarette users as for cigarette smokers. A study comparing 622 exclusive e-cigarette users with 29,082 cigarette smokers found 6-month abstinence rates of 19.6% for e-cigarette users versus 16.3% for smokers.",
      "Text message cessation programs have evidence of effectiveness for quitting vaping in young adults. A randomized trial with 2,588 young adult e-cigarette users found a 24.1% quit rate among those receiving the text message intervention versus 18.6% among controls at 7 months.",
