      "All tobacco products, e-cigarettes, and nicotine pouches deliver nicotine, which is highly addictive. Nicotine causes cravings in the brain that make quitting harder, which is why understanding your reasons for quitting is the first step in any quit attempt.",
      "Set a quit date that is either today or within the next 2 weeks, and commit to stopping completely on that date. Write the date down, tell other people about it, remove all nicotine products, devices, and liquids from your environment, and plan rewards for yourself at milestones along the way.",
      "Build a support team before you quit. Tell family and friends about your quit attempt, ask them for encouragement when cravings hit, and set up regular accountability check-ins so someone is following your progress.",
      "Anticipate your triggers by identifying the timing patterns of your nicotine use, such as after meals, before exams, with coffee, or during stress. Also recognize emotional triggers like boredom, anxiety, and social settings, as well as physical cues, so you can plan ahead for each one.",
      "Common withdrawal symptoms include irritability, trouble concentrating, and cravings. These symptoms usually peak within the first week after quitting and lessen over time.",
      "When a craving or withdrawal symptom hits, use a coping strategy instead of reaching for nicotine. Effective options include deep breathing, going for a run or a walk, and drinking water.",
      "Use proven cessation methods rather than relying on willpower alone. Consult a healthcare provider, ask for behavioral support or counseling, and use toll-free quit lines, text-message programs, or quit apps. Getting professional support increases your chances of success significantly compared to trying to quit on your own.",
      "To stay nicotine-free after quitting, remove all tobacco products and vaping devices from your home and surroundings, and avoid environments where others are using these products, since exposure can trigger relapse.",
      "Track your progress and celebrate milestones as you reach them, including 24 hours, 3 days, 1 week, and 1 month nicotine-free. Marking these wins reinforces your commitment to staying quit.",
      "Relapse is common during quit attempts, but it is not failure. If you slip, adjust your quit plan based on what you learned and continue working toward quitting rather than giving up."
