    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "For World No Tobacco Day 2026, Dr Ghazi Zaatari, chair of the WHO Study Group on Tobacco Product Regulation, warned that a new wave of nicotine and nicotine-like products could fundamentally reshape and expand the addiction market. He noted these products are designed to make initiation easier, reinforce repeated use, and reduce the perception of risk, especially among adolescents and young adults.",
      "Over the past five years, the tobacco industry has increasingly relied on laboratory-synthesized nicotine and chemical analogues instead of tobacco-derived nicotine. These synthetic substances now cost about the same as naturally derived nicotine, enabling products that contain minimal or no tobacco-derived nicotine while still targeting the same brain receptors responsible for addiction.",
      "Modern nicotine products are engineered to deepen dependence through several mechanisms. Nicotine salts allow higher doses of nicotine to be absorbed smoothly, while sweet flavors and cooling sensations reduce harshness. Online marketing emphasizes lifestyle imagery rather than tobacco, and some nicotine analogues are marketed as zero nicotine despite carrying strong dependence potential.",
      "Adolescents are especially vulnerable to nicotine because brain development continues until the mid-20s. Nicotine exposure during this period can alter neural pathways linked to attention, learning, and impulse control.",
      "Tobacco kills 1.2 million people annually in the WHO European Region, including 202,000 deaths attributed to second-hand smoke exposure.",
      "Among adolescents aged 13 to 15 in the WHO European Region, roughly 4 million use tobacco and 4.2 million use e-cigarettes. E-cigarette prevalence in this age group is 14.3 percent, the highest rate globally.",
      "WHO identifies major policy gaps in Europe: only 18 of 53 countries in the region have comprehensive smoke-free laws, just 12 provide national quit lines with covered cessation services, and only 13 have comprehensive advertising bans.",
      "WHO recommends that governments regulate all tobacco and nicotine products including e-cigarettes, implement comprehensive advertising bans, restrict flavors, increase taxation, require plain packaging, strengthen youth protection, and expand access to evidence-based cessation support."
    ]
