    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Each time you use tobacco, nicotine triggers the brain's reward system, and people become addicted to that trigger. People who smoke also get used to the habit of smoking itself, not just the nicotine, and the chemical addiction combined with those habits is what makes quitting hard. It is rare to stop smoking on the first attempt, and even harder without help. You have a better chance of preventing smoking relapse if you have help and if you make a plan.",
      "Nicotine replacement therapy can help you resist cravings while quitting. Nicotine patches are used for long-term replacement, while nicotine gums, lozenges, and nose sprays are used for short-term relief. Some nicotine replacement products require a prescription and others do not, so talk with a healthcare professional to find the right combination for you. The FDA has not approved these products for children, but healthcare professionals sometimes prescribe nicotine-replacement products for teenagers who have serious trouble quitting smoked tobacco.",
      "Knowing what triggers your urge to use nicotine or tobacco helps you make a quit plan. Over time, the feelings you have and the things you do while using tobacco become linked in your brain; for example, taking a work break with others who use tobacco can cause cravings at that time or around those people. To overcome nicotine dependence, identify your triggers and plan how to deal with each one. It helps to write down the triggers you face most days, how you will manage each one, and a list of people who can support you.",
      "Distraction helps because nicotine cravings, while strong, often ease up within minutes. Try setting an alarm for 10 minutes and then pick an activity that distracts you or that you enjoy, or go to a place where smoking and tobacco use are banned. Remind yourself that the urge to smoke will peak and then get better whether or not you use tobacco. Writing down your main reason for quitting and looking at it when a craving hits can help you get through it.",
      "Giving your mouth something to do can replace tobacco during a craving. Chew sugarless gum, or munch on raw carrots, nuts, or sunflower seeds. Keeping mints or candy on hand provides a burst of something tasty. Some people also find that drinking a glass of water helps manage cravings.",
      "Don't cave to a craving by having 'just one' cigarette. Many people who decide to smoke just one cigarette end up using tobacco again at the rate they did before, and some people stop trying to quit once they get down to low levels of use. Even one or two cigarettes a day are linked to a higher risk of disease. Instead of smoking just one, choose a quick-acting medicine for nicotine dependence such as nicotine gum or a lozenge, which is a better bet for managing strong cravings.",
      "Physical activity can help manage both mood and cravings as you quit tobacco. While quitting, you may be quicker to anger, feel frustrated faster, or feel more anxious or tense. Doing something physical that you enjoy takes the edge off these feelings, and it does not have to be strenuous. Ten-minute walks, either indoors or outdoors, can lessen cravings for cigarettes.",
      "If tobacco was your way of dealing with stress, try other ways to relax, since fighting a tobacco craving can itself be stressful. Effective relaxation options include deep breathing, muscle relaxation, yoga, visualization, massage, and listening to calming music.",
      "Setting up a support system helps you resist tobacco cravings. Join an online support group, ask family or friends to be available, or attend an in-person support group. In-person or online counseling helps you practice the skills needed to give up tobacco for good, and the more time you spend with a counselor, the better your treatment results might be. In the United States, you can call 800-QUIT-NOW (800-784-8669) to reach your state's tobacco cessation services, and people age 18 and older can text QUITNOW to 333888.",
      "For long-term success, talk with your healthcare professional about tobacco cessation products, when to start taking them, and their possible side effects. The nicotine patch is a long-acting medicine that slowly releases nicotine over time. Other long-acting medicines that contain no nicotine are bupropion (Wellbutrin SR) and varenicline, both available by prescription. Combining these medicines with a plan helps prevent tobacco relapse.",
      "Reminding yourself of the benefits of quitting strengthens your resolve against cravings. Write down or say out loud your reasons for stopping, such as feeling better, getting healthier, sparing loved ones from secondhand smoke, and saving money. Trying something to beat the urge to use tobacco is always better than doing nothing, and each time you resist a craving you are one step closer to being tobacco-free.",
      "Nicotine cravings get easier to handle after the first weeks of quitting, but they don't go away entirely; over time symptoms lessen and the urge to smoke goes down. For some people, the habit of smoking is the craving that lasts the longest. Smoking relapse within six months of quitting is common, but you can improve your chances with a plan that includes quit-smoking medicines and counseling. Together, medicine and counseling help you take control of your thoughts, manage your response to challenging situations, and handle cravings and nicotine withdrawal."
    ]
