    "chunks": [
      "Quit-smoking products approved by government health agencies can greatly boost the chance of quitting for good, potentially more than doubling the odds of quitting smoked tobacco. The chance of long-term success is even better when counseling is combined with one or more quit-smoking products. These products ease cravings for nicotine, the chemical in smoked tobacco that makes quitting hard, and relieve nicotine withdrawal symptoms after stopping.",
      "Quit-smoking products fall into two main groups. Nicotine replacement products contain nicotine but less than tobacco products; short-acting options include gum, lozenges, and spray, some available without a prescription. Long-acting medicines give ongoing relief from nicotine cravings and withdrawal symptoms; these include the nicotine patch worn on the skin and two prescription medicines that contain no nicotine. Many people benefit from a combination of quit-smoking products. The FDA has not approved these products for children, but healthcare professionals sometimes prescribe nicotine-replacement products for teenagers who have serious trouble quitting smoked tobacco.",
      "Electronic cigarettes (e-cigarettes) heat a liquid that usually contains nicotine, and the user breathes in vapor. The FDA has not approved e-cigarettes as a quit-smoking product, and they are not as safe as nicotine-replacement products. Many people who use e-cigarettes to stop smoking end up using both products rather than quitting. However, if approved treatments do not help after many tries, some healthcare professionals recommend e-cigarettes to help with quitting.",
      "The nicotine patch is a small, sticky patch that releases a slow, steady amount of nicotine into the body through the skin. A new patch is applied every day on a hairless area of skin between the waist and neck, such as the upper arm or chest, without using lotion or moisturizing soap on the area first. The patch is available in various doses without a prescription, is easy to use, controls nicotine cravings and withdrawal symptoms for 24 hours at a time, and can be used along with other quit-smoking aids.",
      "Drawbacks of the nicotine patch: it cannot quickly adjust the amount of nicotine delivered if sudden cravings or withdrawal symptoms occur. It may cause skin itching, rash, or irritation where applied, and may cause upset stomach, insomnia, or vivid dreams. It must be replaced every 24 hours.",
      "Nicotine gum delivers a small amount of nicotine absorbed through the lining of the mouth, with most people using 1 to 2 pieces every 1 to 2 hours as needed. A specific technique is required: bite a piece until it has a peppery taste or tingly sensation, chew briefly, then hold the gum between the gumline and cheek until the taste or tingling stops, and chew and hold again to release more nicotine. Repeat this cycle for about 30 minutes, then spit out the gum because all its nicotine has been used. For best results, do not eat or drink for 15 minutes before chewing the gum.",
      "Nicotine gum is available without a prescription in two strengths, can control sudden nicotine cravings and withdrawal symptoms, and can be combined with other quit-smoking aids. It must be used repeatedly throughout the day to control cravings or withdrawal symptoms. It may cause mouth irritation, jaw soreness, heartburn, hiccups, or upset stomach, and may stick to or damage dental appliances.",
      "Nicotine lozenges are tablets with a small amount of nicotine, placed in the mouth and moved from side to side, dissolving over 20 to 30 minutes while nicotine is absorbed through the lining of the mouth. They are available without a prescription, control sudden cravings and withdrawal symptoms, and come as mini-lozenges that deliver nicotine faster. They do not need chewing and do not stick to dental appliances, and they can be used along with other quit-smoking aids. Downsides: they must be used repeatedly throughout the day and may cause mouth irritation, hiccups, heartburn, and upset stomach.",
      "Nicotine nasal spray delivers a solution containing a small dose of nicotine into the nostrils, absorbed through the lining of the nose; the recommended dose is 1 to 2 sprays in each nostril once an hour. It works faster than other nicotine-replacement products, lets the user control the dose as needed throughout the day, controls sudden cravings and withdrawal symptoms, and can be combined with other quit-smoking aids. It is available only by prescription and must be used repeatedly throughout the day. It may cause an irritated throat, watery eyes, runny nose, a burning feeling in the nose, sneezing, and coughing, and may not be a good choice for people with a nasal or sinus condition.",
      "Bupropion (Wellbutrin SR) is a prescription medicine, also used to treat depression, whose sustained-release form is approved to help people stop smoking. It is thought to lessen tobacco cravings and withdrawal symptoms by boosting levels of certain brain chemicals. It takes days to build up in the blood, so people typically start taking it a week or two before quitting smoking, and it must be taken twice a day. It is a pill, can be used with other quit-smoking aids, and may lessen the weight gain many people experience after quitting. Side effects can include dry mouth, headache, upset stomach, dizziness, or trouble sleeping; changes in mood or behavior require contacting a healthcare professional right away. Bupropion is not recommended for people with seizures or an eating disorder.",
      "Varenicline is a prescription medicine that reduces cravings for tobacco, controls nicotine withdrawal symptoms, and has effects on the brain that lessen the pleasurable feelings of smoking. It takes days to build up in the blood, so people typically start taking it a week or two before quitting smoking, and it must be taken twice a day. It is a pill that can be used along with other stop-smoking aids. It may cause upset stomach, vomiting, headache, a change in taste, trouble sleeping, and vivid or strange dreams; changes in mood or behavior require calling a healthcare professional right away.",
      "The best way to quit smoking for good is to use more than one type of treatment: combine a quit-smoking product with a program that includes support from professionals trained to treat nicotine dependence. Nicotine dependence happens when a person needs nicotine and cannot stop using it. Joining a community stop-smoking group or starting in-person or telephone counseling also improves the chance of success."
    ]
