      "To diagnose nicotine dependence, a healthcare professional may ask questions or use a questionnaire to measure how dependent you are on nicotine. Knowing your degree of dependence helps determine the right treatment plan. The more cigarettes you smoke each day and the sooner you smoke after waking up, the more dependent you are.",
      "It is rare to stop smoking successfully on your first attempt, especially without help. You are much more likely to be able to stop smoking if you use medicines and counseling. Both treatments work, and they work especially well when used together.",
      "Some quit-smoking treatments are known as nicotine replacement therapy because they contain varying amounts of nicotine. A long-acting form is the nicotine patch placed on the skin, while short-acting products include nicotine gums, lozenges and nose sprays. Some nicotine replacement therapies require a prescription, but others do not.",
      "Two quit-smoking medicines, bupropion (Wellbutrin SR) and varenicline, do not contain nicotine and are available by prescription. Like nicotine replacement products, they can ease nicotine cravings and withdrawal symptoms and make it more likely you will stop smoking for good. Using more than one quit-smoking product may produce better results. Even for products sold without a prescription, talk with a healthcare professional first about which products are right for you, when to start them, and possible side effects.",
      "Medicines help you cope with quitting by easing withdrawal symptoms and cravings, while counseling helps you practice the skills you need to give up tobacco for good. The more time you spend with a counselor, the better your treatment results may be. In individual or group counseling you learn techniques to help you stop smoking, and many hospitals, healthcare plans, healthcare professionals and employers offer treatment programs, including intensive outpatient programs at some medical centers.",
      "If medicines and counseling do not help a person stop smoking after many tries, some healthcare professionals recommend electronic cigarettes, which heat a liquid that usually contains nicotine into a vapor. However, e-cigarettes are a controversial option because their long-term health effects are unclear, and many people who use them to stop smoking end up using both products rather than quitting. Do not use e-cigarettes unless your healthcare professional recommends them because approved treatments did not help enough.",
      "Do not substitute another type of tobacco use for smoking, because tobacco in any form is not safe, and forms of nicotine not approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration may not be safe. Products to avoid as substitutes for smoked tobacco include dissolvable tobacco products, smokeless tobacco, nicotine lollipops and balms, cigars, pipes, hookahs, and nicotine pouches.",
      "Social support is key to leading a stable, smoke-free life. Ask family, friends and co-workers to support and encourage you, and be direct about what would help you most. Support groups such as Nicotine Anonymous offer coaching and support from others trying to quit, often at little or no cost. Telephone quit lines provide convenient access to trained counselors; in the U.S., call 800-QUIT-NOW (800-784-8669) to connect to your state's quit line. Text messaging services and mobile apps can send reminders and tips, and web-based programs such as BecomeAnEX provide free personalized support, interactive guides and tools, and discussion groups.",
      "To prepare for a quit-smoking appointment, write down your smoking triggers, listing the situations where you are most likely to smoke or where smoking has become a ritual. Note any symptoms that may be related to smoking and how long you have had each one, make a list of all medications including vitamins, herbs and supplements, and consider inviting a family member or friend to help remember the information shared.",
      "A healthcare professional assessing nicotine dependence will likely ask how many cigarettes you smoke each day and how soon after waking you smoke. Other common questions include whether you have tried to stop smoking before and what worked or did not work, what is motivating you to quit now, whether you have health conditions possibly related to smoking such as heart disease or diabetes, and whether smoking has caused problems at work or in relationships."
