      "The Cochrane systematic review 'Exercise interventions for smoking cessation' (Ussher and colleagues, 2019 update) examined whether exercise programmes, alone or added to a smoking cessation programme, help people achieve long-term abstinence of at least six months. The review included 24 randomised controlled trials with 7279 adult participants, with evidence current to May 2019. Twenty-two trials studied smokers wishing to quit, and two focused on relapse prevention among people who had recently stopped smoking.",
      "Across 21 analysed trials with 6607 participants, adding exercise to smoking cessation support did not show evidence of improving quit rates at six months or longer compared with cessation support alone (risk ratio 1.08, 95% confidence interval 0.96 to 1.22, with no statistical heterogeneity). The evidence was judged low certainty because of imprecision and suspected publication bias. Results did not differ by exercise type: cardiovascular-type exercise alone (17 studies), resistance training alone (one study), combined cardiovascular and resistance exercise (one study), or unspecified exercise (two studies). Results were also unchanged when trials at high risk of bias or trials in special populations were excluded.",
      "For relapse prevention, two trials with 453 participants provided very low-certainty evidence that adding exercise to a relapse prevention programme did not improve long-term abstinence compared with relapse prevention alone (risk ratio 0.98, 95% confidence interval 0.65 to 1.47). The very low certainty reflected a high risk of bias in one study and imprecise effect estimates.",
      "The review authors concluded there is no evidence that adding exercise to smoking cessation support improves abstinence compared with support alone, but the evidence is insufficient to rule out a modest benefit. It could be that exercise does not help quit rates at all, or that supporting people to exercise modestly increases quit rates; current evidence cannot distinguish between these. Because the estimates were of low or very low certainty, future trials may change these conclusions, and there is currently insufficient evidence to support exercise as a specific aid to smoking cessation.",
      "In the included trials, most exercise interventions were supervised, group-based cardiovascular-type exercise (such as walking or stationary cycling) supplemented by a home-based exercise programme, combined with a multi-session cognitive behavioural smoking cessation programme; the comparator was usually the cognitive behavioural cessation programme alone. Eleven of the 24 studies enrolled women only and one enrolled men only, most participants were fairly inactive, and follow-up ranged from 6 to 16 months. Studies took place in community and healthcare settings in Canada, Finland, France, New Zealand, the UK, and the USA.",
      "Although long-term quit rates were not improved in trials, experimental studies have consistently shown that temporarily abstinent smokers experience reduced psychological withdrawal symptoms and reduced desire to smoke after a single bout of cardiovascular-type exercise. Longer bouts of exercise tend to produce a more sustained reduction in cravings and withdrawal, while even brief bouts with a brief effect may help abstinent smokers cope with a temporary spike in cravings. Several studies have also shown that a bout of exercise delays the next cigarette or favourably changes smoking behaviour, likely mediated through reduced cravings and withdrawal.",
      "Several mechanisms have been proposed for how exercise might aid quitting. Exercise has some similarities to smoking in stimulating the central nervous system, increases beta-endorphin levels in smokers, and may act as an alternative reinforcer to smoking, depending on how rewarding physical activity is for the individual. There is some evidence exercise reduces attentional bias to smoking-related cues that trigger cravings, while distraction appears unlikely to play a major role, and changes in cortisol concentration were unrelated to changes in cravings across four studies.",
      "Among the included trials, nine assessed effects on cigarette withdrawal symptoms or cravings, and there was little evidence that the exercise interventions had a beneficial effect on these outcomes over time. One trial reported significantly lower somatic withdrawal symptoms and less sleep disturbance in the exercise group during treatment, but no group difference in craving. Only five of the studies explicitly promoted exercise as a coping strategy for managing cigarette cravings, which the authors note as a limitation, since acute laboratory evidence consistently shows a bout of exercise can alleviate cravings and withdrawal symptoms.",
      "Concern about weight gain is common when quitting smoking, and exercise is often suggested to manage it. Twelve of the included studies examined weight change and one assessed body mass index, but overall there was little evidence that exercise interventions affected weight change during smoking cessation. One trial observed that participants receiving exercise alone gained significantly less weight by end of treatment than those receiving only cognitive-behavioural support, but most studies found no difference in weight gain at end of treatment or at 3-, 6-, or 12-month follow-ups, and several were too small to detect a treatment effect.",
      "There is some evidence that a bout of exercise reduces cigarette cravings even when a nicotine lozenge is being used, suggesting exercise could address psychosocial and physical needs not met by nicotine replacement therapy; alternatively, exercise may add little if medication has already lowered cravings. More broadly, being physically active has been positively associated with intending to quit, initiating a quit attempt, confidence in maintaining abstinence, quit success, and a reduced risk of relapse, and smokers who meet physical activity guidelines show a significant reduction in mortality. Regular exercise also carries general physical and mental health benefits, including reduced symptoms of depression, for both people who quit and people who continue to smoke."
