      "The Cochrane living systematic review 'Electronic cigarettes for smoking cessation' (Lindson and colleagues, version published 10 November 2025) examined the safety, tolerability, and effectiveness of e-cigarettes for helping people who smoke achieve long-term abstinence. It included 104 completed studies with 30,366 adults who smoked, of which 61 were randomised controlled trials, covering evidence published up to 1 March 2025. Most studies took place in the USA (48 studies) and the UK (21 studies). Searches are run and screened monthly, and the review is updated when relevant new evidence becomes available.",
      "Electronic cigarettes (e-cigarettes or vapes) are handheld devices that heat a liquid, usually containing nicotine and flavourings, so users inhale nicotine in a vapour rather than smoke. Because they do not burn tobacco, regulated e-cigarettes do not expose users to the same levels of chemicals that can cause diseases in people who smoke conventional cigarettes. Many people use e-cigarettes to help them stop smoking tobacco.",
      "There is high-certainty evidence that nicotine e-cigarettes increase quit rates (abstinence for at least six months) compared to nicotine replacement therapy such as patches or gum, with a risk ratio of 1.55 (95% CI 1.28 to 1.88; 9 studies, 2703 participants). In absolute terms, this translates to roughly three additional successful quitters per 100 people (95% CI 2 to 5 more) when using nicotine e-cigarettes instead of nicotine replacement therapy.",
      "Nicotine e-cigarettes probably also increase quit rates compared to e-cigarettes without nicotine, based on moderate-certainty evidence (risk ratio 1.34, 95% CI 1.06 to 1.70; 7 studies, 1918 participants). In absolute terms this might lead to an additional two quitters per 100 (95% CI 0 to 4 more), suggesting the nicotine itself, not just the hand-to-mouth behaviour, contributes to quitting success.",
      "Compared to behavioural support only or no support at all, quit rates may be higher for people using nicotine e-cigarettes (risk ratio 1.78, 95% CI 1.42 to 2.25; 11 studies, 6819 participants), representing about three additional quitters per 100 (95% CI 2 to 5 more). This evidence is rated low-certainty due to risk of bias in the contributing study designs.",
      "In absolute success rates from the Cochrane review, for every 100 people using nicotine e-cigarettes to stop smoking, 8 to 11 might successfully stop for at least six months. This compares with about 6 of 100 people using nicotine replacement therapy, 6 of 100 using e-cigarettes without nicotine, and only 4 of 100 having no support or behavioural support alone.",
      "The unwanted effects reported most often with nicotine e-cigarettes were throat or mouth irritation, headache, cough, and nausea. These appear similar to what people experience when using nicotine replacement therapy, and they tended to reduce and dissipate over time as people continued using the e-cigarettes. Rates of adverse events were probably similar between nicotine e-cigarettes and nicotine replacement therapy, and probably little to no different between nicotine and non-nicotine e-cigarettes, though non-serious unwanted effects may be somewhat more common with nicotine e-cigarettes than with behavioural or no support.",
      "Serious adverse events were rare across all study arms in the review, and there was insufficient evidence to determine whether their rates differed between nicotine e-cigarettes and any comparator. The reviewers did not detect evidence of serious harm from nicotine e-cigarettes, but note that longer and larger trials are needed to fully evaluate safety, since included safety data only extend up to two years of use. This conclusion applies specifically to people using e-cigarettes to stop smoking, not to people who have never smoked.",
