      "Most people who stop smoking gain weight, usually in the first few months after quitting. This weight gain can discourage some people from making a quit attempt and risks offsetting some, but not all, of the health advantages of quitting. A 2021 Cochrane review (Hartmann-Boyce et al., 'Interventions for preventing weight gain after smoking cessation') examined whether weight-control interventions help and whether they undermine quitting, with evidence current up to October 2020.",
      "The Cochrane review on post-cessation weight gain included 116 studies in total: 37 studies of specific weight-control programmes in 11,514 people trying to stop smoking, and 83 studies of other cessation methods (exercise, nicotine replacement therapy, varenicline, bupropion, fluoxetine, e-cigarettes) covering 46,248 people that also measured weight change. Outcomes were measured at end of treatment, 6 months, and 12 months, with weight change reported only in people abstinent from smoking.",
      "An intermittent very low calorie diet (VLCD) with full meal replacement and intensive dietitian support significantly reduced post-cessation weight gain at end of treatment (mean difference -3.70 kg, 95% CI -4.82 to -2.58), but showed no clear benefit at 12 months (-1.30 kg). The VLCD also increased the chances of smoking abstinence at 12 months (risk ratio 1.73, 95% CI 1.10 to 2.73). However, these conclusions rest on a single trial of 287 participants, and a second small trial found that no one completed the VLCD intervention or achieved abstinence.",
      "Acceptance-based programmes for weight concerns teach self-regulation skills, such as how to deal with cravings, alongside accepting some weight gain. In the Cochrane review, these programmes made little to no difference to weight gain itself, but they increased quit rates at 6 months (risk ratio 1.42, 95% CI 1.03 to 1.96; 4 studies, 619 participants). The benefit was no longer statistically clear at 12 months (risk ratio 1.25, 95% CI 0.76 to 2.06).",
      "Personalized weight-management support, which includes feedback on personal goals and a personal energy (calorie) prescription, reduced post-cessation weight gain at end of treatment by about 1.11 kg on average (95% CI -1.93 to -0.29), though evidence of longer-term benefit at 12 months was lacking (-0.44 kg, CI -2.34 to 1.46). In contrast, detailed weight-management education without personalized assessment, planning, and feedback did not reduce weight gain and may actually have reduced smoking cessation rates at 12 months (risk ratio 0.66, 95% CI 0.48 to 0.90).",
      "Exercise interventions for smoking cessation led to minimal or no weight reduction at end of treatment (mean difference -0.25 kg), but weight was reduced by about 2 kg at 12 months (mean difference -2.07 kg, 95% CI -3.78 to -0.36; 3 studies, 182 participants). The review authors note this delayed effect is counterintuitive, since adherence to exercise regimens usually declines rather than increases over time, and call for further studies of exercise interventions.",
      "Among stop-smoking medications, both bupropion and fluoxetine limited weight gain at the end of treatment, each by about 1 kg on average (bupropion mean difference -1.01 kg across 10 studies with 1,098 participants; fluoxetine -1.01 kg across 2 studies). There was no evidence of lasting benefit for bupropion at 12 months, and no fluoxetine studies provided 12-month data. Some older pharmacological agents tested for limiting post-cessation weight gain (dexfenfluramine, phenylpropanolamine, naltrexone) reduced weight gain at end of treatment, while effects of ephedrine plus caffeine, lorcaserin, and chromium were too imprecise to be useful.",
      "Nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) probably reduces post-cessation weight gain slightly: moderate-certainty evidence showed about 0.5 kg less weight gain at end of treatment (mean difference -0.52 kg; 21 studies, 2,784 participants) and a similar small effect at 12 months (-0.37 kg; 17 studies, 1,463 participants), though long-term estimates were imprecise.",
      "Varenicline makes little difference to weight gain. High-certainty evidence showed weight change was only very modestly lower at the end of treatment (mean difference -0.23 kg; 14 studies, 2,566 participants), and a low-certainty, imprecise estimate suggested possibly higher weight at 12 months. The review authors state that further studies are unlikely to change the end-of-treatment finding for varenicline.",
      "Overall, the Cochrane review concluded there is no intervention with moderate-certainty evidence of a clinically useful effect on long-term weight gain after quitting smoking. Importantly, there is also no moderate- or high-certainty evidence that interventions designed to limit weight gain reduce people's chances of successfully quitting smoking. NRT, bupropion, fluoxetine, and varenicline all slightly reduced weight gain in the short term, but any 12-month benefit was very uncertain and modest at best.",
      "For people worried about weight when quitting smoking, the key takeaways from the Cochrane evidence are: stopping smoking is the best thing you can do for your health; weight gain typically happens in the first few months after quitting; and in comparison groups without weight interventions, average weight gain at end of treatment was around 1.45 kg. Researchers still need data on whether using e-cigarettes to quit smoking affects post-cessation weight change, and future trials of weight-gain-prevention approaches should follow people for at least 6 to 12 months."
