      "A 2022 Cochrane systematic review (Jackson and colleagues, 'Mindfulness for smoking cessation') assessed whether mindfulness-based interventions help people stop smoking and whether they affect mental health outcomes. The review included 21 randomised controlled trials with 8,186 participants, with evidence searched up to 15 April 2021. All included studies measured smoking cessation at six months or longer, using the most rigorous definition of abstinence available, on an intention-to-treat basis.",
      "Mindfulness involves focusing attention on your thoughts and feelings and observing them without judgment as they arise and pass away. It is believed to help people better control their thoughts and feelings rather than be controlled by them. Because stopping smoking gives rise to distressing urges to smoke and low mood, mindfulness-based treatments are proposed to improve people's ability to cope with negative affective states, cravings, and other symptoms of nicotine withdrawal.",
      "Four types of mindfulness-based smoking cessation interventions were studied: mindfulness training, which involves training in mindfulness-based meditation; acceptance and commitment therapy (ACT), which does not teach meditation but encourages people to embrace their thoughts and feelings rather than fighting them while making committed behaviour change; distress tolerance training, which provides parts of ACT and also presents people with situations that make them want to smoke so they can practise the skills they have learnt; and yoga, which increases awareness of breathing and encourages a connection between mind and body.",
      "Across the 21 included studies, the treatments tested were mindfulness training (8 studies), acceptance and commitment therapy (8 studies), yoga (3 studies), and distress tolerance training (2 studies). These were compared with other stop-smoking treatments that were equally time-intensive (such as counselling), less intensive treatments (such as brief advice), or no treatment. Most studies recruited adults from the community; 15 took place in the USA, 2 in Hong Kong, and 1 each in Brazil, Ireland, and Cyprus. Reviewers judged 4 studies to be at low risk of bias, 9 at unclear risk, and 8 at high risk.",
      "Mindfulness training showed no clear benefit or harm on quit rates compared with intensity-matched smoking cessation treatment (risk ratio 0.99, 95% CI 0.67 to 1.46; 3 studies, 542 participants; low-certainty evidence), less intensive smoking cessation treatment (RR 1.19, 95% CI 0.65 to 2.19; 5 studies, 813 participants; very low-certainty evidence), or no treatment (RR 0.81, 95% CI 0.43 to 1.53; 1 study, 325 participants; low-certainty evidence). In each comparison the confidence interval encompassed benefit, harm, and no difference. One study of mindfulness-based relapse prevention also found no clear benefit or harm over no treatment (RR 1.43, 95% CI 0.56 to 3.67; 86 participants; very low-certainty evidence).",
      "Acceptance and commitment therapy (ACT) showed no clear benefit or harm on quit rates compared with less intensive behavioural treatments, including nicotine replacement therapy alone (RR 1.27, 95% CI 0.53 to 3.02; 1 study, 102 participants; low-certainty evidence), brief advice (RR 1.27, 95% CI 0.59 to 2.75; 1 study, 144 participants; very low-certainty evidence), or less intensive ACT (RR 1.00, 95% CI 0.50 to 2.01; 1 study, 100 participants; low-certainty evidence). Heterogeneity across studies comparing ACT with intensity-matched smoking cessation treatments was high (I-squared 82%), so a pooled result was not reported for that comparison.",
      "Distress tolerance training showed no clear benefit or harm on quit rates compared with intensity-matched smoking cessation treatment (RR 0.87, 95% CI 0.26 to 2.98; 1 study, 69 participants; low-certainty evidence) or less intensive smoking cessation treatment (RR 1.63, 95% CI 0.33 to 8.08; 1 study, 49 participants; low-certainty evidence). Yoga likewise showed no clear benefit or harm compared with intensity-matched smoking cessation treatment (RR 1.44, 95% CI 0.40 to 5.16; 1 study, 55 participants; very low-certainty evidence). Excluding studies at high risk of bias did not substantially alter these results.",
      "In absolute terms, quit rates at six months or longer were similar between groups: with intensity-matched comparison treatments, about 16 per 100 people quit in both the mindfulness training and control groups. Against less intensive treatment, an estimated 14 per 100 quit with mindfulness training versus 11 per 100 with the comparator, and against no treatment, 10 per 100 with mindfulness training versus 12 per 100 without. These differences were not statistically reliable given the wide confidence intervals.",
      "Nine studies reported on changes in mental health and well-being while quitting, including depression, anxiety, perceived stress, and negative and positive affect. One study found a greater reduction in perceived stress in participants who received a face-to-face mindfulness training programme versus an intensity-matched stop-smoking programme at six-month follow-up. However, the remaining eight studies found no clinically meaningful differences in mental health and well-being between participants who received mindfulness-based treatments and those who received another treatment or no treatment (very low-certainty evidence). Variation in measures and methods between studies meant the data could not be meta-analysed.",
      "The review authors concluded there is currently no clear evidence that mindfulness-based treatments help people stop smoking or improve their mental health and well-being compared with intensity-matched treatment, less intensive treatment, or no treatment. The evidence was of low and very low certainty due to risk of bias, inconsistency, and imprecision, so further evidence may very likely change this interpretation. The authors note that even if mindfulness is only as successful as other behavioural support in enhancing long-term quit rates, it may be preferable to some smokers if it improves mental health; future trials should use active comparators, biochemical verification of abstinence, and follow-up of at least six months."
