      "A large Cochrane systematic review titled 'Smoking cessation for improving mental health' examined whether quitting smoking improves or worsens mental health. It analyzed 102 studies with over 169,500 participants, directly addressing the common misconception that smoking helps manage stress and mental illness symptoms. The review concluded that mental health does not worsen as a result of quitting smoking, and that quitting is associated with small to moderate improvements in mental health.",
      "The belief that smoking relieves stress is largely a misreading of the nicotine withdrawal cycle. Chronic tobacco smoking causes neuroadaptations in nicotinic pathways in the brain, and withdrawal symptoms begin returning roughly 20 minutes after a cigarette as blood nicotine levels decline. Smokers then mistake the temporary relief of those withdrawal symptoms for genuine stress relief, when in fact each cigarette is treating discomfort that smoking itself created.",
      "Quitting smoking is associated with reduced anxiety symptoms. Across 15 studies with 3,141 participants, people who quit showed a standardized mean difference of -0.28 (95% CI -0.43 to -0.13) in anxiety compared with those who continued smoking, though this was rated low-certainty evidence. This contradicts the fear that giving up cigarettes will make people more anxious.",
      "Quitting smoking is associated with reduced depression symptoms. Across 34 studies with 7,156 participants, quitters showed a standardized mean difference of -0.30 (95% CI -0.39 to -0.21) in depression symptoms compared with continuing smokers. For mixed anxiety and depression symptoms, the improvement was similar (SMD -0.31, 95% CI -0.40 to -0.22 across 8 studies with 2,829 participants) and was rated moderate-certainty evidence.",
      "Beyond anxiety and depression, quitting smoking was linked to broader emotional improvements. Quitters showed reduced stress symptoms (SMD -0.19 across 4 studies with 1,792 participants), increased positive affect (SMD 0.22 across 13 studies with 4,880 participants), and improved psychological quality of life (SMD 0.11 across 19 studies with 18,034 participants). Social quality of life did not decline after quitting, countering the worry that giving up cigarettes harms social life.",
      "Quitting smoking may also reduce the chance of developing new mental health disorders, not just improve existing symptoms. Quitters had lower incidence of new mixed anxiety and depression (odds ratio 0.76 across 3 studies with 8,685 participants) and lower incidence of new anxiety disorders (odds ratio 0.61 across 2 studies with 2,293 participants). There were insufficient data to pool estimates for new depression diagnoses.",
      "The mental health improvements from quitting smoking appeared in both general populations and people with pre-existing psychiatric conditions. The reviewed studies included 23 studies of people with psychiatric conditions, 16 of people with chronic physical conditions, 4 of pregnant women, and 3 of post-surgical patients. The typical participant was about 45 years old and smoked around 20 cigarettes per day with medium nicotine dependence (median dependence score 5.4), so the findings apply to established, fairly heavy smokers.",
      "Healthcare providers sometimes hesitate to encourage quitting in people with mental illness for fear it will destabilize them, but this review suggests that concern is unfounded, since quitting was associated with improved rather than worsened mental health even in psychiatric populations. This matters because smoking prevalence among people with mental illness remains high, around 32% in the UK. A noted limitation is that all included studies carried serious risk of bias from time-varying confounding, such as changes in alcohol or drug use, medication changes, and major life events during the study period, so the authors call for studies with more advanced methods."
