      "Clinical guidance for e-cigarette (vaping) cessation was developed through a modified Delphi consensus process run from September through December 2021, involving 24 international experts in tobacco and e-cigarette cessation plus a panel of people with lived experience of vaping. The process produced 24 evidence-informed recommendations and 2 consensus statements across eight domains, covering assessment, treatment, dual use, pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, harm reduction, and relapse prevention. Because the evidence base for e-cigarette cessation specifically remains weak, most recommendations were adapted from established tobacco cessation research.",
      "Vaping prevalence has risen sharply. In Canada in 2021, 5.2% of adults aged 15 and over had used e-cigarettes in the past 30 days, up from 2% in 2013, with usage at 13% among ages 15-19, 17% among ages 20-24, and 4% among ages 25 and over; 84% of users used nicotine-containing products. In England and the US, 6-8% of youth aged 16-19 used e-cigarettes on at least 20 of the past 30 days in 2022, up from 2% in 2017.",
      "Dual use, meaning concurrent smoking of tobacco cigarettes and vaping, carries serious risks: greater toxicant exposure, breathing difficulties, increased nicotine dependence, elevated cardiovascular disease risk, and worse overall health outcomes than using either product alone. For people who dual use, expert guidance is to first advise completely switching from smoking to vaping only, and then to encourage progressing from vaping to complete cessation. Experts did not reach consensus on whether dual users should quit both products simultaneously or sequentially, so a person-centered discussion of the options is recommended.",
      "Clinicians are advised to ask all clients about their vaping status, and assessments may also address dual use, physical and mental health, and social and environmental factors. Standardized nicotine dependence tools can inform treatment intensity: for adults, the E-FTND, EDS, or PS-ECDI; for youth, the HONC or EDS. People who previously smoked and are now quitting vaping should be monitored for relapse to smoking.",
      "All populations, including people who previously smoked, should be advised to eventually quit vaping entirely. A minimum treatment duration of 8-12 weeks is suggested for vaping cessation. Adults, youth, and people with mental illness can be offered behavioral therapy either with or without pharmacotherapy, while pregnant or breastfeeding individuals should receive behavioral therapy as first-line treatment, with nicotine replacement therapy considered second-line.",
      "Pharmacotherapy options for vaping cessation in adults, youth, and people with mental illness include nicotine replacement therapy (NRT), varenicline, cytisine, and bupropion. For pregnant or breastfeeding individuals, experts did not reach consensus on pharmacotherapy and advise a person-centered approach. Further research is still needed on how medications compare across different nicotine delivery methods.",
      "Effective behavioral support formats for quitting vaping include one-on-one counseling, smartphone apps, web-based programs, text messaging programs, and telephone quitlines or helplines. These behavioral strategies are recommended for all populations, with or without accompanying medication.",
      "For people who continue to vape, device-related harm reduction guidance includes: do not modify products or add substances such as THC, vitamin E acetate, or oils; avoid illicit or black market e-liquids and devices; avoid harmful flavors including cinnamon, cherry, menthol, and any products containing diacetyl; and follow the device manufacturer's instructions.",
      "Relapse prevention guidance for vaping cessation includes offering continued support after a relapse rather than ending treatment, and extending pharmacotherapy beyond the quit date. Dual users who relapse to smoking should have cessation treatment reinitiated, while exclusive vapers who are unsuccessful at quitting can be advised on harm reduction strategies. Regular screening for vaping is recommended for all populations, and former smokers at high risk of relapsing to smoking may continue vaping as a less harmful alternative.",
      "Key gaps remain in vaping cessation science: the direct evidence base is weak, most guidance is extrapolated from tobacco cessation research, and rigorous clinical trials of vaping-specific interventions are still needed. There is also no expert consensus on terminology, with disagreement over using 'nicotine use disorder' versus 'nicotine dependence' to describe problematic vaping."
