      "Sleep problems are a common and often overlooked part of quitting smoking. Research examining over 1,100 smokers found that sleep disturbance increased significantly for nearly everyone in the first week after their quit date, regardless of whether they used a nicotine patch, varenicline, or a placebo. This means disrupted sleep is a normal part of the early quitting process and not a sign that something is wrong.",
      "When people successfully stayed off cigarettes for the first week, those using active cessation medication (a nicotine patch or varenicline) experienced noticeably more sleep disturbance than those on placebo. Among people who relapsed or never quit, all groups had similar, smaller increases in sleep problems. This pattern suggests that for successful quitters on medication, poor sleep comes from a combination of nicotine withdrawal and a side effect of the treatment itself.",
      "Standard smoking cessation medications are good at easing most withdrawal symptoms like cravings and irritability, but they do not reduce withdrawal-related sleep disturbance. In fact, the nicotine patch and varenicline were associated with greater sleep problems even though they controlled other withdrawal symptoms. If you are quitting and notice trouble sleeping, know that the medication is still helping with other aspects of withdrawal.",
      "The three specific sleep complaints tracked during quitting were general sleep problems, insomnia (trouble falling or staying asleep), and abnormal or vivid dreams. These were measured at baseline and again one week after the quit date. Withdrawal-related sleep disruption tends to peak early, often within the first 24 to 72 hours after quitting, so the worst nights are usually in the first few days.",
      "How quickly your body breaks down nicotine appears to influence sleep during quitting. Slow nicotine metabolizers reported more overall sleep disturbance than normal metabolizers. However, metabolizer status did not change how the medications affected sleep, so the extra sleep difficulty for slow metabolizers held regardless of which treatment was used.",
      "Sleep problems present before quitting can hurt your chances of staying smoke-free. People who reported greater sleep disturbance at baseline, before their quit date, were more likely to relapse by the end of treatment around week eleven. This link held even after accounting for which medication people used. Interestingly, the change in sleep quality during the first week of quitting did not predict relapse, so it is the pre-existing sleep problems that matter most.",
      "Because cessation medications do not fix quitting-related sleep disturbance, researchers suggest pairing them with treatments aimed directly at sleep. Options include cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia (CBT-I) or approved sleep aids, which may improve the odds of quitting successfully. This is especially worth considering for people who already struggle with sleep before they try to quit.",
      "The study behind these findings was a randomized controlled trial across four academic medical centers, comparing placebo, the nicotine patch, and varenicline in moderately dependent smokers who smoked at least ten cigarettes a day. About 45 percent of participants were abstinent one week after their quit date. The authors caution that their brief sleep questionnaire and single follow-up may have missed the true peak of sleep disruption, which can occur in the first one to three days after quitting."
