      "Smoking cessation reduces the risk of 12 cancers that are causally linked to smoking: lung, larynx, oral cavity and pharynx, esophagus, pancreas, bladder, stomach, liver, colon and rectum, kidney, cervix, and acute myeloid leukemia. The longer a person stays quit, the lower the risk becomes across these cancer types.",
      "For lung cancer, risk decreases to about half that of continuing smokers roughly 10 to 15 years after quitting. Quitting by age 40 eliminates most of the excess lung cancer risk compared with people who continue to smoke long term. Relative risk estimates fall to about 0.7 to 0.8 within 10 years of quitting and to about 0.3 from 10 to 19 years after quitting.",
      "For cancers of the larynx, oral cavity, and pharynx, risk drops by roughly 30 percent within 5 years of quitting, by about 50 percent from 5 to 9 years out, and by about 80 percent after 20 or more years. Esophageal cancer risk is about 30 percent lower in former smokers who quit 10 or more years ago compared with continuing smokers.",
      "Pancreatic cancer risk approaches that of people who never smoked roughly 20 years after quitting. Bladder cancer risk drops by about 50 percent after a few years of quitting, although the largest studies found it took more than 10 years for risk to fall to half that of continuing smokers.",
      "Quitting smoking after a cancer diagnosis improves survival. Across ten cohort studies covering 10,975 patients, continued smoking was associated with a median relative risk of all-cause mortality of 1.82 compared with quitting. For non-small cell lung cancer, quitters had a relative risk of death of 0.34 versus persistent smokers, and for small cell lung cancer the hazard ratio was 0.55.",
      "Carbon monoxide from smoking clears from the body quickly: it has a short half-life and smoking-related carbon monoxide is cleared within several days of quitting. This is one of the earliest measurable physiological recoveries after stopping smoking.",
      "Blood vessel function begins to recover soon after quitting. Endothelium-dependent vasodilation improves within 24 hours of cessation, and 2 to 4 weeks of quitting is associated with increases in progenitor cells that indicate the blood vessel lining is repairing itself. In one trial, flow-mediated dilation improved by about 1 percentage point after one year of cessation.",
      "Clotting-related blood factors normalize over months to years after quitting. Fibrinogen levels fall within about 2 weeks and become similar to those of never smokers roughly 5 years after cessation. Von Willebrand factor decreased significantly at 2, 6, and 12 months after quitting, and markers such as D-dimer, platelet factor-4, and beta-thromboglobulin were significantly lower 6 and 12 months after cessation.",
      "Inflammation declines with time since quitting. C-reactive protein becomes similar in former smokers and never smokers about 5 years after cessation, high-sensitivity CRP decreases as more time passes since quitting, and white blood cell counts normalize roughly 5 years after cessation. Smoking also raises triglycerides and LDL cholesterol and lowers HDL cholesterol, and these lipid measures improve with cessation.",
      "Cardiovascular disease is a major motivator for quitting: about 92.1 million U.S. adults have one or more forms of CVD, with coronary heart disease accounting for 43.2 percent of CVD deaths and stroke for 16.9 percent. Because smoking is a leading cause of cardiovascular disease, the rapid recovery of blood vessel function, clotting factors, and inflammation after quitting translates into substantial reductions in cardiovascular risk over time."
