      "Anger is a major emotional challenge during smoking cessation, and people who tend toward anger as a stable personality trait have a harder time quitting. A study of 72 daily smokers (each smoking at least 15 cigarettes per day for two or more years) examined how trait anger affected mood, stress hormones, and the risk of relapse during the first attempt to quit. The findings show that managing anger may be a key part of staying smoke-free.",
      "During the first 24 hours of abstinence, smokers with higher trait anger experienced significantly worse withdrawal. They reported larger increases in craving, more overall withdrawal symptoms, more physical symptoms, and higher levels of in-the-moment (state) anger compared to lower-anger smokers. In other words, an angry temperament amplified almost every uncomfortable part of early quitting.",
      "Trait anger was also linked to stress-hormone changes in the body during abstinence. Smokers high in trait anger showed elevated ACTH (a stress hormone signal) at baseline and a tendency toward reduced cortisol during abstinence. These physiological differences may help explain why anger-prone quitters feel more dysregulated and stressed when they stop smoking.",
      "Higher trait anger strongly predicted faster relapse. Among participants who scored 20 or higher on the trait anger scale, 13 of 14 relapsed within just one week of quitting. The high-anger group lasted an average of only 8.5 days before relapse, versus 13.2 days for the low-anger group.",
      "A trait anger score of 20 emerged as a meaningful threshold for relapse vulnerability in this research. People who recognize anger as a persistent personal tendency may benefit from building specific anger-management and stress-coping skills before and during a quit attempt, since unmanaged anger is one of the clearest early warning signs of returning to smoking.",
      "The study measured anger using the Spielberger State-Trait Anger Expression Inventory, and tracked craving and withdrawal with the Minnesota Nicotine Withdrawal Scale and the brief Questionnaire of Smoking Urges. Participants were monitored across normal smoking, a 24-hour quit period with saliva and blood sampling, a laboratory stress session, and four weekly follow-ups. This combination allowed researchers to connect day-one withdrawal experiences directly to real-world relapse over the following weeks."
