    "referenceOnly": false,
    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "People begin using nicotine for many reasons, including appealing flavors, peer influence, or to manage stress and anxiety. However, nicotine use can rapidly develop into an addiction that actually intensifies stress and anxiety, trapping users in a harmful cycle. It may only take a small amount of tobacco product use to lead to nicotine dependence.",
      "A widespread misconception is that nicotine relieves stress and anxiety. According to Truth Initiative research, 81% of teens and young adults said they started vaping e-cigarettes to reduce stress, anxiety, or depression. In reality, nicotine addiction worsens these conditions over time rather than relieving them.",
      "The nicotine addiction cycle begins when nicotine triggers a release of dopamine in the brain, creating feelings of pleasure and relaxation, and the brain learns to associate nicotine with reward. When nicotine is absent, dopamine levels drop and the pleasure sensations disappear. Cravings and withdrawal symptoms then emerge as the brain becomes dependent on nicotine to maintain dopamine levels and chemical balance.",
      "Nicotine withdrawal produces symptoms such as irritability, anxiety, headaches, and restlessness, which can feel overwhelming as the brain struggles to function normally without nicotine. To relieve these withdrawal symptoms, users seek out nicotine again, which completes and reinforces a continuous cycle of dependence. Breaking this loop is the central challenge of quitting nicotine.",
      "Young people are especially vulnerable to nicotine addiction because their brains are still developing. Exposure to harmful chemicals from e-cigarettes may increase the risk of cancer and adverse reproductive outcomes, and research suggests e-cigarettes may carry risks similar to cigarettes regarding depression in young people. Despite these risks, motivation to quit is high: 67% of young adult nicotine users planned to quit in 2026.",
      "Effective strategies for overcoming nicotine withdrawal include exercise, distractions, community support, and nicotine replacement therapy. The EX Program, a free digital quitting tool developed by Truth Initiative with the Mayo Clinic, can increase the odds of quitting by up to 40%. It provides personalized quit plans, daily supportive text messages with tips and expert advice, and an established online community of people quitting nicotine."
    ]
