    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Nicotine withdrawal affects both the mind and the body, causing cravings and emotional distress when quitting vaping. According to Truth Initiative survey data, about 67% of young adults ages 18-24 plan to quit nicotine for 2026, with improved mental and physical health as their primary motivation. Free digital quitting support, including a personalized quit plan and an online community, is available through the EX Program, a collaboration between Truth Initiative and Mayo Clinic.",
      "Exercise is an effective way to handle nicotine cravings during withdrawal because it provides distraction while boosting endorphins and dopamine, which improves mood. It does not require structured workouts: light activities like stretching or taking a short walk are enough to redirect attention away from a craving.",
      "Nicotine cravings during withdrawal produce emotional symptoms such as irritability, anxiety, and depression, as well as physical symptoms such as restlessness, headache, and insomnia. However, individual cravings typically last only a few minutes. Finding an engaging distraction, such as folding laundry, reading, painting nails, knitting, calling a friend, or going for a walk, helps people ride out acute withdrawal, and each craving successfully weathered builds confidence for the next one.",
      "Leaning on support systems strengthens a quit attempt: encouragement from friends, family, and other people who are quitting makes it easier to get through nicotine withdrawal. Online quit communities, such as the EX Program community, give access to advice from Mayo Clinic tobacco cessation specialists and the lived experiences of former tobacco and vape users.",
      "Many people use nicotine to manage stress, so finding alternative stress solutions is essential when quitting vaping. Meditation, breathing exercises, and grounding techniques redirect attention to the present moment and replace nicotine-dependent stress management with healthier coping mechanisms.",
      "Celebrating accomplishments, even small early milestones like the first few hours without nicotine, boosts resilience during a quit attempt. Sharing pledges and milestones with others, for example on a community celebrations board like the one in the EX Program, reinforces progress and motivation to stay quit."
    ]
