    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Many people put off quitting smoking, or relapse after quitting, because they fear gaining weight. It is true that many smokers put on weight after they quit, but understanding why it happens can help you beat the odds rather than letting the fear keep you smoking.",
      "Weight gain after quitting smoking has clear physiological causes. Nicotine suppresses appetite and elevates metabolism, so when you quit you feel hungrier and your body returns to a normal metabolism. Your taste buds and sense of smell also come back to life after quitting, making food more appealing. In addition, with cigarettes out of the picture, many people use food to occupy their mouths and to cope with stress.",
      "When weighing weight gain against smoking, remember that weight gain after quitting can be temporary, while the effects of smoking may not be. Extra weight will not cause lung cancer. And although extra pounds increase the risk of developing or aggravating diabetes, smoking does too.",
      "Weight gain after quitting smoking is not inevitable. A review of 62 studies published in the British Medical Journal found that about 16 percent of smokers actually lost weight after quitting. For another 37 percent of quitters, weight gain was less than 11 pounds. Many people feel so empowered by quitting, and inspired by their newfound stamina, that they start exercising and eating healthier.",
      "If fear of weight gain is holding you back from quitting tobacco, a useful technique is to notice your negative thoughts about your weight and question them. Ask yourself whether these thoughts are accurate, and whether they could be excuses to keep smoking.",
      "A practical cognitive technique for quitters worried about weight: challenge specific negative thoughts. If your jeans fit more snugly and you think 'I'm worse off now than before I quit' or 'People will think less of me if I gain 10 pounds,' test those ideas. Even if you must buy a larger pair of jeans, you are not truly worse off than when you were addicted to tobacco. If a co-worker gained 10 pounds after beating tobacco, you would likely congratulate her on a tremendous accomplishment rather than think poorly of her.",
      "Counter each negative thought about post-quit weight gain with a positive one. For example, replace it with thoughts like 'Now I don't feel like an outcast at work, and I'm saving $250 a month.' Reframing in this way helps keep fear of weight gain from derailing a quit attempt."
    ]
