    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Many people gain weight when they quit smoking cigarettes; on average, people gain 5 to 10 pounds (2.27 to 4.54 kilograms) in the months after giving up smoking. Worry about extra weight leads some people to put off quitting, but not smoking is one of the best things you can do for your health, and there are concrete steps that keep weight under control during a quit.",
      "Weight gain after quitting happens for several reasons tied to how nicotine affects the body. Nicotine speeds up metabolism, increasing the calories the body uses at rest by about 7% to 15%, so without cigarettes the body may burn food more slowly. Cigarettes also reduce appetite, so after quitting you may feel hungrier. In addition, smoking is a habit, and after quitting you may crave high-calorie foods as a replacement for cigarettes.",
      "Physical activity helps control weight after quitting smoking because it burns calories and also helps ward off cravings for unhealthy foods or cigarettes. People who already exercise may need to exercise longer or more often to burn the calories that nicotine's metabolism boost used to remove.",
      "Shopping strategically supports weight control while quitting smoking: decide what to buy before getting to the store and make a list of healthy foods like fruit, vegetables, and low-fat yogurt that you can indulge in without too many calories. Stock up on low-calorie finger foods that keep your hands busy, such as sliced apples, baby carrots, or pre-portioned unsalted nuts. Sugar-free gum is also useful because it keeps your mouth busy without adding calories or exposing teeth to sugar.",
      "Healthy eating habits help prevent weight gain after quitting smoking. Make a healthy meal plan ahead of time so you can combat cravings when they hit; it is easier to say no to fried chicken nuggets if you are looking ahead to a roast chicken with vegetables for dinner. Never let yourself get too hungry, because if you must eat right away you are more likely to reach for a diet-busting option, and learning to eat filling foods helps ward off hunger.",
      "Sleep and drink choices affect weight while quitting smoking. People who often do not get enough sleep are at greater risk of putting on extra weight. Alcohol, sugary sodas, and sweetened juices go down easily but add up and can lead to weight gain; try sparkling water with 100% fruit juice or herbal tea instead.",
      "Even if you put on some weight while staying off cigarettes, the quit is worth it and you should congratulate yourself: your lungs and heart will be stronger, your skin will look younger, your teeth will be whiter, and you will have better breath. Your hair and clothes will smell better, you will have more money when you are not buying cigarettes, and you will perform better in sports and other physical activities. Giving up the habit takes time physically and emotionally, so take one step at a time.",
      "If you have tried to quit smoking and relapsed, a health care provider may suggest nicotine replacement therapy, which comes as a patch, gum, nasal spray, or inhaler and delivers small doses of nicotine throughout the day to ease the transition to going totally smoke free. If you gain weight after quitting and cannot lose it, ask your provider to recommend an organized weight-loss program with a good track record that helps you lose weight in a healthy, lasting way."
    ]
