    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Cigarette smoking remains the leading cause of preventable death and disease in the United States, accounting for 490,000 premature deaths per year, and about 34 million U.S. adults smoke cigarettes. Knowing the negative health effects of tobacco can help on the path to quitting, but it is also important to know that many people who smoke do not quit for good on their first attempt and need several tries before they succeed. If you want to quit, do not give up, and know you are not alone.",
      "Nicotine, the highly addictive drug present in tobacco products, is what keeps people smoking even when they know cigarettes harm their health. Cigarettes are designed to deliver nicotine quickly to the brain, and this rapid delivery is the main reason people continue to use tobacco even when they want to quit.",
      "In 2015, nearly 70 percent of current adult smokers in the United States said they wanted to quit. In 2018, about 55 percent of adult smokers had made a quit attempt in the past year, but only about 8 percent were successful in quitting for 6-12 months. It commonly takes several attempts to quit for good, so even small successes count as wins.",
      "Each quit attempt is a step forward rather than a failure. You may find that the next time you try to quit, you can go longer without a cigarette than the last time, or you might discover that exercise helps stave off your cravings. With each quit attempt you learn new techniques and learn more about yourself, moving one step closer to being a former smoker; each attempt can be thought of as practice for quitting for good.",
      "When you first quit smoking, you may feel discomfort as the nicotine leaves your system, so it helps to know the symptoms in advance and plan ways to handle them. After quitting, you may experience temporary depression, disrupted sleep patterns, irritability, anxiety, difficulty concentrating, and increased appetite. While uncomfortable, these withdrawal symptoms should only last a few weeks. It is also a good idea to talk to your doctor about your quit plan, since they may have advice suited to your situation.",
      "Many people who used to smoke find that certain places, occasions, and behaviors—such as drinking coffee, going out with friends, or particularly stressful events—can bring up an urge to smoke even after withdrawal symptoms have ended. Noticing these trigger situations and making a plan to divert your urge to smoke can help you stay smoke-free for good.",
      "Nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) refers to FDA-approved therapies such as nicotine skin patches, gum, and lozenges that can help through the initial part of quitting by relieving cravings and lessening withdrawal symptoms. NRTs deliver measured amounts of nicotine without the toxic chemicals from cigarette smoke. When used properly, NRTs are safe and effective and can double the chances of quitting cigarettes successfully.",
      "Even if you have tried quitting with nicotine replacement therapy before, experimenting with different NRT options can help you find what works for you. NRTs are considered safe enough that multiple methods—for instance the patch and the gum—can be used at the same time. You may also start using NRT before quitting cigarettes, which could help you avoid some of the initial symptoms that sometimes occur when first quitting. NRTs are available both by prescription and over-the-counter for adults age 18 and over, and include skin patches that deliver nicotine through the skin, nicotine gum that releases nicotine as you chew it, and nicotine lozenges that dissolve in your mouth.",
      "Telephone quit line counseling is an effective strategy for quitting smoking, and combining counseling with nicotine replacement therapy can be more successful than nicotine replacement therapy alone."
    ]
