    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "Tobacco products are addictive because they contain nicotine, a highly addictive chemical compound present in the tobacco plant. Nicotine is what keeps people using tobacco products even when they want to stop. All tobacco products contain nicotine, including cigarettes, heat-not-burn (heated) tobacco products, cigars, smokeless tobacco such as dip, snuff, snus, and chewing tobacco, hookah tobacco, and most e-cigarettes.",
      "Using any tobacco product can lead to nicotine addiction because nicotine can change the way the brain works, causing cravings for more of it. Some products, like cigarettes, are designed to deliver nicotine to the brain within seconds, which makes it easier to become dependent and harder to quit. While nicotine occurs naturally in the tobacco plant, some products contain additives that may make it easier for the body to absorb more nicotine.",
      "Nicotine is what keeps people using tobacco, but it is the thousands of chemicals in tobacco and tobacco smoke that make tobacco use so deadly. This toxic mix of chemicals, not nicotine itself, causes the serious health effects among tobacco users, including fatal lung diseases such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and cancer. Some of these lung-damaging chemicals are also found in some e-cigarette aerosols.",
      "Tobacco products containing nicotine pose different levels of health risk to adult users. Combustible products that burn tobacco are the most harmful; cigarettes, for example, deliver more than 7,000 chemicals along with the nicotine that makes them hard to quit. FDA-approved nicotine replacement therapies such as gums and lozenges are the least harmful, while noncombustible products like heat-not-burn tobacco, smokeless tobacco, and e-cigarettes fall somewhere in between.",
      "FDA-approved nicotine replacement therapies (NRTs) are safe and effective products that contain nicotine and are designed to help adults quit smoking by delivering small amounts of nicotine to the brain without the toxic chemicals found in cigarette smoke. NRTs such as nicotine skin patches, gum, and lozenges can help through the early part of quitting by relieving cravings and lessening nicotine withdrawal symptoms. When used properly, NRTs can double the chances of successfully quitting cigarettes.",
      "There are no FDA-approved NRTs for youth use; parents should talk to a health care provider about treatment options for youth. Because no tobacco product is safe, youth and adults who do not already use tobacco products should not start using e-cigarettes.",
      "E-cigarettes can generally be a lower-risk alternative for adults who already smoke cigarettes, but they are not risk-free: they deliver harmful chemicals and contain highly addictive nicotine, and more high-quality research on short- and long-term health outcomes is still needed. For adults who smoke, switching completely from cigarettes to e-cigarettes may reduce exposure to many harmful chemicals. It is important to switch completely, because long periods of dual use of cigarettes and e-cigarettes can cause harms to health similar to, or in addition to, those from smoking cigarettes alone.",
      "To date, FDA has authorized 45 e-cigarettes. These products underwent rigorous scientific review, including toxicologic assessments, and were found by FDA to meet the statutory public health standard. Nicotine, including nicotine salt, is also listed by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) as an acute hazardous waste, and discarded or neglected vaping products may contain harmful substances including unused e-liquid.",
      "Because their brains are still developing, young people have a higher risk of becoming addicted to the nicotine in tobacco products than adults. The younger a person is when they start using tobacco, the more likely they are to become addicted, and nicotine exposure during adolescence can disrupt normal brain development. Because of nicotine's powerfully addictive nature and major effects on the developing brain, no tobacco products are safe for youth to use.",
      "Nicotine can cross the placenta when a pregnant person uses tobacco products, which can negatively impact the baby. Possible effects include premature labor, low birth weight, respiratory failure at birth, and even sudden infant death syndrome (SIDS). People who use tobacco can experience negative effects on their reproductive health, pregnancies, and babies, and anyone considering having a child should consult their doctor and learn how to quit.",
      "In January 2025, FDA proposed a rule to limit the nicotine level of cigarettes and certain other combusted tobacco products to a minimally or nonaddictive level. This reduction would lower the chances that future generations become addicted to cigarettes and would make it easier for people who currently smoke to quit or switch to lower-risk tobacco products."
    ]
