    "retrievalDate": "2026-06-10",
    "chunks": [
      "In January 2018, the FDA launched \"Every Try Counts,\" the agency's first smoking cessation campaign. The campaign was built on the key research insight that it takes many smokers multiple quit attempts to achieve long-term cessation. It also underscored the health benefits of quitting and used positive messaging to increase motivation for smokers to try to quit again. The campaign's goal was to reach smokers living in 35 U.S. counties with high adult smoking rates and encourage them to quit.",
      "To guide the development of \"Every Try Counts,\" the FDA conducted focus groups to determine which messages resonated with adult smokers. Messages that worked included using real experiences from smokers who were trying to quit or who succeeded at quitting for good after repeated attempts, and reframing failure as an opportunity to learn what works for each individual. Emphasizing small steps to help smokers \"practice the quit\" and celebrating each quit attempt also resonated. Non-judgmental messages encouraging repeat attempts until smokers quit for good felt manageable and empowering to adult smokers.",
      "The \"Every Try Counts\" campaign delivered the right content at the right time by serving tailored digital content based on geographic location, in and around convenience stores and gas stations where tobacco products are sold. It delivered ads to smokers who were open to quitting using behavioral, lifestyle, and demographic information, and reminded them that resources are available to help them every step of the way.",
      "\"Every Try Counts\" campaign messages encouraging smokers to quit were deliberately displayed in and around places where cigarettes are sold, such as gas stations and convenience stores. These locations typically feature cigarette advertisements and are places where smokers face triggers that can keep them smoking, making them strategic points for cessation messaging.",
      "For \"Every Try Counts,\" the FDA partnered with the National Cancer Institute to develop cessation resources encouraging smokers to take steps toward quitting. Quitting tools offered on EveryTryCounts.gov included text message programs, a mobile quitting app, trained cessation counselors reachable through online chat or by phone, and information about different cessation methods.",
      "In early 2020, \"Every Try Counts\" shifted to a national digital campaign to reach a broader audience, and its messages reached over 45 million adult smokers. In total, the campaign's advertising generated over 769 million digital views and sent more than 1.6 million unique visitors to EveryTryCounts.gov, prompting over 15,000 sign-ups for text message programs designed to help smokers quit.",
      "Although \"Every Try Counts\" advertising ended in 2020, the FDA continues to develop a range of free adult cigarette cessation education materials. These materials are available in English and Spanish and promote the benefits of quitting cigarettes. Campaign print ads carried titles such as \"You Didn't Fail at Quitting\" and \"Quitting Isn't a Perfect Process,\" reinforcing the message that past unsuccessful attempts are part of the path to quitting for good."
    ]
