      "E-cigarettes are the most commonly used tobacco product among middle- and high-school students in the United States. According to a 2024 federal survey, approximately 1.63 million middle and high school students use e-cigarettes. About 1 in 4 teen e-cigarette users report daily use. Nearly 88% of teen users choose flavored e-cigarettes, and fruit flavors are the most popular.",
      "E-cigarettes are devices that produce an aerosolized liquid (vapor) that usually contains nicotine and other chemicals; the liquid may also contain marijuana, herbs, waxes, and oils. These products go by many names, including vapes, vape pens, personal vaporizers, e-cigars, pod systems, mods, and e-hookah.",
      "E-cigarettes can be hard for parents to recognize because they may resemble traditional tobacco products like cigarettes, cigars, and pipes, or common gadgets like pens, flashlights, USB flash drives, fidget spinners, gaming controllers, car key fobs, smart watches, and even asthma inhalers. In 2022 the FDA warned companies for marketing 15 e-cigarette products packaged to look like toys, food, or cartoon characters.",
      "The nicotine found in most e-cigarettes is addictive and can harm adolescent brain development, specifically the parts of the brain that control attention, learning, mood, and impulse control. Youth who use e-cigarettes are also more likely to smoke traditional cigarettes in the future. Even some e-cigarettes marketed as containing 0% nicotine have been found to contain nicotine.",
      "The most popular e-cigarettes contain highly concentrated nicotine salts that deliver much more nicotine than traditional cigarettes. E-liquid is dangerous on contact: skin exposure can cause nicotine poisoning, with symptoms including vomiting, sweating, dizziness, increased heart rate, lethargy, seizures, and difficulty breathing.",
      "E-cigarette vapor contains harmful chemicals including propylene glycol or ethylene glycol (chemicals used to make antifreeze), diethylene glycol, and aldehydes such as formaldehyde, which is ranked as one of the top cardiovascular toxins. The e-juice may also contain cancer-causing chemicals, heavy metals, and ultrafine particles that can get deep into the lungs.",
      "Secondhand vapor from e-cigarettes is harmful to growing lungs, with studies showing long-term effects on lung health, function, and development in children exposed to it. In addition, e-cigarette devices themselves have exploded in some cases, causing burns or fires.",
      "In 2019 the CDC investigated an outbreak of e-cigarette, or vaping, product use-associated lung injury (EVALI). By February 2020 there were more than 2,800 hospitalizations and 68 deaths from EVALI across the United States. Tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) products and vitamin E acetate were linked to most cases.",
      "No e-cigarette is FDA-approved as a smoking-cessation treatment, and there are safer, proven treatments available to quit smoking. Although it is illegal to sell e-cigarettes to youth under age 21, teens can still order them online, so age restrictions alone do not prevent access."
