      "According to the American Academy of Pediatrics, 90% of tobacco users began using tobacco before age 18, and more than 16% of high school students report current use of a tobacco product. Roughly 2.5 million young people used e-cigarettes in 2022. Nearly 1 in 10 middle schoolers and 2 in 10 high schoolers have used smokeless tobacco.",
      "Nicotine use during adolescence can harm the parts of the brain that control attention, learning, mood, and impulse control. Evidence also shows that kids who use nicotine face greater risks of developing other substance use disorders later in life. E-cigarettes contain nicotine derived from tobacco and are classified as tobacco products by the FDA, so they carry these same adolescent brain risks.",
      "Hookah is not a safe alternative to cigarettes for teens: a typical one-hour hookah session is equivalent to smoking 100 cigarettes. Smokeless tobacco is also widely used by youth, with nearly 1 in 10 middle schoolers and 2 in 10 high schoolers reporting use.",
      "Flavors are a major driver of youth nicotine initiation: more than 80% of young people say the first tobacco product they tried was flavored. Tobacco companies reach youth through fruit and candy flavorings, celebrity endorsements, social media campaigns on Instagram, TikTok, YouTube and Snapchat, retail displays, event sponsorships, free samples, and scholarship contests. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends banning added flavors, including menthol, from all tobacco products.",
      "Price is a powerful deterrent for young nicotine users: youth and young adults are 2 to 3 times more sensitive to higher tobacco prices than adults, so price increases are an effective way to discourage youth tobacco use. The American Academy of Pediatrics also recommends enforcing the 2019 federal law restricting tobacco purchases to people age 21 and older, and eliminating online and vending machine sales of tobacco products.",
      "Media exposure influences teen smoking: adolescents see about 275 instances of tobacco use in PG-13 movies each year. Reducing movie tobacco exposure to 10 or fewer instances yearly could reduce adolescent smoking by an estimated 18%. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends restricting tobacco use imagery in movies and media and prohibiting tobacco advertisements visible to children.",
